Imagine a very long webpage with a lot of sections (think HTML specification on one page). If the user requests a specific section (e.g. page.html#section7), what if the web server streamed this section first and then the other sections?
Playback order.
Beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
HTML for Section 7
HTML for Sections 1, 2, 3 etc.
Then the browser would ensure that sections 1 to 6 are displayed over section 7 on the website.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to implement elements with JavaScript again. I just want a very long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed in this way, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id="sec2"></div>
et cetera (abbreviated form)
section 7...
Section 1...
Section 2...
etc.
It wouldn't be streamed in sequence, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed in sequence.
You can reorder documents like this without JS too. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters to tell the server which part you want to show first. When reordering the parts, you have several options:
Using CSS.
Template with sections use.
Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows non-sequential streaming, but the browser then arranges the content in DOM order.
But the idea with the slots looks promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 do you want the browser to reorder the DOM?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first, so the user can see it as soon as possible. If that could work without affecting the DOM order, that would be good, then the browser would ensure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
It shall therefore be section 7 streamed first, but the final result should look as though all sections were streamed in sequence.
